Teir'Dal/Dark Elf<br>
12 Necromancer<br>
<br>
I know what you're thinking. &quot;Just who is this irresistible creature who has an insatiable love for the dead?&quot; Well, let's begin by throwing out the notion that I'm just another living dead girl.<br>
<br>
Don't get me wrong. I'm just as mercurial as the next Teir’Dal, given to moments of mirth and brooding. However, I do not define myself by the stereotype of one who practices my Art. I'm not some angst-riddled loner living under some curse. I certainly don't consider myself Damned. Death isn't my burden, it's my passion. It is a blessing from Innoruuk that I have been chosen to be its harbinger.<br>
<br>
I felt the call to the crypts at a very young age. When other children were playing their games of make-believe, I was already living with the reality of death. My mother's life was taken by the wife of the man who is my father. Oh, please, don't act so surprised. Sex and death aren't novel concepts; and violent acts of passion are age old traditions. Ah, but I digress. Please forgive my lapse.<br>
<br>
My father's wife stole me from my mother's dying arms and introduced me to her own family and house as her daughter. It was no act of mercy, but one of revenge and ambition in equal parts. <br>
<br>
For the most part I was accepted into the family as one of their own. My new siblings greeted with the same treachery they did each other. &quot;Mother&quot; instructed us all, early on, that if we desired the luxuries of her wealthy household then we would have to earn those privileges. No, she didn't mean through &quot;hard work&quot;; we weren't set to sweeping floors and carrying out the garbage like slaves. Our only task was to win her favor.<br>
<br>
Oh, how she toyed with us. Looking back I can see the benefits from her ways. After all, I could never trust anyone more than my brothers and sisters, and I didn't trust them at all. They were the competition. To see them coddled by mother would push me to such lengths. Obviously those vulgar displays of emotion were meant to bring out my hate and they were always successful. Deceit, treachery, and violence became my toys of choice. The plan was always simple: Do whatever it takes.<br>
<br>
Surviving my childhood was no small feat and living beyond my adolescence was just short of a miracle. I had the fortune of being my father’s favorite. His discreet guidance insured my success. It was his desire to see me well that landed me into the care of the dreadful gnome, Nyntiki. <br>
<br>
A powerful necromancer in her own right, Nyntiki sensed in me what I had already known for myself. I was destined to walk hand in hand with Lady Death. Nyntiki gave me a glimpse at my potential and set me on the path of Bones. Under her harsh tutelage I honed that raw potential into a crude Art and entered the profession of Necromancer. There was never any doubt about my path. The dead have been whispering into my ears since before I could speak. Now fully grown, they walk with me as company and servants to my cause.<br>
<br>
It was Nyntiki who first pointed out the mark of the Tears upon my back. I remember the moment clearly as nothing had ever stopped the gome mid-lashing before. She seemed amazed by it and came at me again. This time sans whip. There was question after question though. When finally realzing I had no answers she began to speak of Veeshan and her brood of dragons. I didn't understand her point at the time, but she insisted that one day I would.<br>
<br>
Getting back to family matters, it was a miracle my siblings also survived our childhoods. A pity that father did not. He was cut down by my sister, making my eldest brother, Tsadrin head of our household. Mother fled before the knife was put into her back. She lives on and remains a powerful force in our lives who manipulates from the very shadows. We may never be free of her influence and that is something of a boon and still a curse.<br>
<br>
Having fulfilled the tradition of patricide and our youths behind us, my brood split apart. We each went our separate ways to pursue our separate goals.<br>
<br>
I had the recent luck to run across a warrior named Illistyl Silverleaf in Oasis. She had only just managed to survive a battle with one of the Sand Giants who bully about the desert. I helped her as I could, forging a pact between us that traded out my health for her hurts and then bandaging her with my meager skills. As I assisted I couldn't help but spy the mark wrought on the back of her hand. I asked her about it and showed her the one I bear on my back and we found them identical. She seemed enthused to find this out and directed me to the Tears with haste.<br>
<br>
So, here I am in the present moment, touring your hall with wide open eyes and certain understanding about my future and destiny alongside you. <br>
<br>
Have I come unknowingly into my new home?<br>
<br>
Will you have me? <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/ueilunedakallabeth.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Eiluned Akallabeth</A> at: 10/21/02 3:08:54 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=375D88><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/usteoff.showPublicProfile?language=EN>steoff</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(10/21/02 3:30:26 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/ftearsofveeshan25764frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=154.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Greetings, Tears..</span><hr size=1> *grin*<br>
